message.text:
Yesterday, Maj Gen Konata Crumbly, commander of the Georgia Air National Guard, visited Soldiers at the Georgia Army National Guard Readiness Center. 

He also met with the New Jersey All-Hazards Incident Management Team at a logistics hub in Macon. 

During his visits a few soldiers were coined for their dedication and hard work. 

This crucial hub sends Hurricane Helene Relief items to point of distribution centers throughout South Georgia.

U.S. Air National Guard photos by Tech. Sgt. Michelle Self

FINE ARTIST-
WESTERN & PITTSBURGH STEELER ART

FREELANCE GRAPHIC ARTIST-
HIGH-END T-SHIRT ART

FL & WY

Denny is Art Rooney, Jr's personal portrait artist. Mr. Rooney is on of the owners and Vice President of the Pittsburgh Steelers. Denny has also done two portraits of Troy Polamalu for the Steeler Front Office that were shown at the 75th Anniversary Show at the Heinz Museum. His portraits of former Steeler, Jack Butler were displayed at the HOF in Canton for the same 75th Anniversary Show. Art Jr. just bought the two Polamalus. The pencil study was just donated to the Heinz Museum and the oil painting just landed at the NFL Hall of Fame. Denny is truly honored and humbled.

Denny is currently working on six more former Steeler portraits for Mr. Rooney. Bill Dudley and Elbie Nickel right now. He will be doing L.C., Shell, Swan, Stallworth and one more to be determined. He is also working with Rocky Bleier doing his portrait. Denny is constantly being asked to show my art at all the sports shows in the "Burgh." Several of these will be featured there.

Denny Karchner’s “Western Artwork” was spawned from a deep passion for the love of a pencil and paint at a very young age. He has been producing “pencils” since the tender age of three-years-old and after a 34-year hiatus, has recently returned to paints. Here, you will find the newest in a series in oils, acrylics and pencils. These are Denny’s tightest and most intense works ever.”

Denny Karchner’s passion and love for “pencil and paints” are gaining him increased notoriety among museums and private collectors. Over the last few years, Denny has worked closely with the Buffalo Bill Historical Center in Cody and has had art included in their Annual Art Auctions. In the Fall of 2005, Denny had two pieces accepted into the prestigious “Booth Western Art Museum” for their permanent private collection. Those pieces are “Horse Capture” and “Chief Tosh-A-Wah.”

Since moving to the beautiful Lower Southfork, in Cody, Wyoming, Denny is now “living the dream” and concentrating heavily on his fine art career, painting the faces of the “old and new west.”
